## MVC Controller Lifecycle

The framework's `Controller<TModel, TView, TResult>` provides a reactive pipeline driven by model changes, view availability, and user input. Each virtual method has a specific role -- do not conflate them.

### Method Responsibilities

| Method | Triggered by | Purpose | View access? |
|--------|-------------|---------|--------------|
| `Initialize(TView, CT)` | Each view checkout from pool | One-time data population (pre-show) | Yes |
| `Update(CancellationToken)` | Model change (automatic) | Sync model from external services/state | No |
| `Update(TView, CancellationToken)` | Model change + view available | Push model state into view setters | Yes |
| `Run(TView, CancellationToken)` | After open animations | Flow control and user input only | Yes |

### View Lifecycle Execution Order

Each time a controller's view is checked out from the pool, the framework executes:

```
Checkout → Initialize(view) → Update(view) → Open Animation → Run(view) → Close Animation → Release
```

`Initialize` and `Update` run BEFORE the view is visible. `Run` starts AFTER open animations complete. This ordering guarantees the view is fully populated before the player sees it.

**`Initialize(TView, CancellationToken)`** -- Runs once per view checkout, before `Update` and before open animations. Use for one-time data population with values that are known at checkout time and will not change during the view's lifecycle. This is NOT called once per controller lifetime -- it runs every time the view is checked out from the pool (including re-checkouts of the same pooled view instance).

```csharp
protected override UniTask Initialize(LeaderboardView view, CancellationToken token)
{
    GameSessionResult result = _sessionResult.Value;
    view.SetHeader(_levelDefinition.DisplayName);
    view.SetCurrentScore(result.RoundReached, result.TotalEnemiesKilled);
    view.SetTopScores(_scoreService.GetTopScores(_levelDefinition.LevelId));
    return base.Initialize(view, token);
}
```

**`Update(CancellationToken)`** -- Called every time `Model` changes (via `RunModel` loop). Use this to read external services and update the model with `Model = Model with { ... }`. No view reference -- model-only work.

```csharp
protected override void Update(CancellationToken token)
{
    if (Model.Score != _scoreService.CurrentScore)
    {
        Model = Model with { Score = _scoreService.CurrentScore };
    }
}
```

**`Update(TView, CancellationToken)`** -- Called after `Update(CT)` when a view exists. Auto-cancelled and restarted on model change. Push model state into view setters here.

```csharp
protected override UniTask Update(LobbyView view, CancellationToken token)
{
    view.SetPlayerName(Model.PlayerName);
    view.SetRegion(Model.Region);
    view.SetPlayerCount(Model.PlayerCount);
    return UniTask.CompletedTask;
}
```

**`Run(TView, CancellationToken)`** -- Runs after open animations complete. This is the input/flow loop: await user actions, branch, call sub-controllers, return a result. Do NOT put per-frame updates or model refresh logic here.

```csharp
protected override async UniTask<MenuResult> Run(MenuView view, CancellationToken token)
{
    while (true)
    {
        Input input = await NextInput(view, token);
        switch (input)
        {
            case Input.Play: return MenuResult.Play;
            case Input.Settings:
                await _settingsController.Run(token);
                break;
            case Input.Quit: return MenuResult.Quit;
        }
    }
}
```

### Button Input Pattern

Use the framework's awaitable `OnClick(Button?, CancellationToken)` -- never `onClick.AddListener` or C# event delegates.

```csharp
// GOOD -- awaitable, analytics-integrated, auto-cleanup on cancellation
protected override async UniTask<VoidReturn> Run(DialogView view, CancellationToken token)
{
    await OnClick(view.ConfirmButton, token);
    return VoidReturn.Return;
}

// GOOD -- multi-button with enum mapping
private async UniTask<Input> NextInput(MenuView view, CancellationToken token)
{
    return (Input)await UniTask.WhenAny(
        OnClick(view.PlayButton, token),
        OnClick(view.SettingsButton, token),
        OnClick(view.QuitButton, token)
    );
}

// BAD -- manual listener management, no analytics, leak-prone
view.OnPlayClicked += OnPlay;
try { await tcs.Task; }
finally { view.OnPlayClicked -= OnPlay; }
```

Views expose `Button` references as properties. Do NOT wrap buttons in C# events on views:

```csharp
// GOOD -- view exposes the raw Button
public Button PlayButton => _playButton;
public Button QuitButton => _quitButton;

// BAD -- view wraps buttons in events (forces listener pattern on controller)
public event Action? OnPlayClicked;
private void Awake() { _playButton.onClick.AddListener(() => OnPlayClicked?.Invoke()); }
```

### Model Immutability

Models are `record` types. Update them via `with` expressions -- never mutate fields directly on the controller:

```csharp
// GOOD -- triggers RunModel pipeline (Update -> Update(view) automatically)
Model = Model with { LoadedAmmo = Model.LoadedAmmo - 1 };

// BAD -- mutable field on controller, bypasses reactive pipeline
private int loadedAmmo;
loadedAmmo--;
```

Setting `Model` triggers the `RunModel` loop which calls `Update(CT)` then `Update(view, CT)` automatically. Call `Refresh()` to re-trigger without changing the model reference.

This is also how `Run` triggers view updates -- setting `Model` from within the input loop causes `Update(TView)` to re-run, keeping view-binding in its proper layer rather than calling view setters directly from `Run`.

### View Data Flow: Separation of Concerns

Each view-facing method has a specific data-flow role. Do not conflate them:

| Method | Data role | When to use |
|--------|-----------|-------------|
| `Initialize(TView)` | One-time setup | Data known at checkout, won't change (headers, labels, static lists) |
| `Update(TView)` | Model-driven refresh | Data that changes when `Model` changes (reactive binding) |
| `Run(TView)` | Flow control only | Await input; trigger view updates via `Model = Model with { }` |

When `Run` receives new data (from user input, awaited services, or sub-controller results), do NOT call view setters directly. Instead, update the model -- the framework re-runs `Update(TView)` automatically:

```csharp
// GOOD -- Run triggers view refresh via Model; Update owns view binding
protected override UniTask Update(ScoreView view, CancellationToken token)
{
    view.SetScore(Model.Score);
    view.SetMultiplier(Model.Multiplier);
    return UniTask.CompletedTask;
}

protected override async UniTask<VoidReturn> Run(ScoreView view, CancellationToken token)
{
    while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        var input = await NextInput(view, token);
        if (input == Input.DoubleDown)
            Model = Model with { Multiplier = Model.Multiplier * 2 };
    }
    return default;
}

// BAD -- Run calls view setters directly, bypasses reactive pipeline
protected override async UniTask<VoidReturn> Run(ScoreView view, CancellationToken token)
{
    while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        var input = await NextInput(view, token);
        if (input == Input.DoubleDown)
            view.SetMultiplier(Model.Multiplier * 2); // view and model out of sync
    }
    return default;
}
```

**Full SoC example** -- all three methods cooperating on one controller:

```csharp
public sealed class ShopController : Controller<ShopModel, ShopView, ShopResult>
{
    [Dependency] private readonly IInventoryService _inventory = default!;
    [Dependency] private readonly ICursorService _cursor = default!;

    protected override UniTask Initialize(ShopView view, CancellationToken token)
    {
        view.SetShopName(Model.ShopName);
        view.SetItemCatalog(Model.Items);
        return base.Initialize(view, token);
    }

    protected override UniTask Update(ShopView view, CancellationToken token)
    {
        view.SetPlayerGold(_inventory.Gold);
        view.SetSelectedItem(Model.SelectedIndex);
        return UniTask.CompletedTask;
    }

    protected override async UniTask<ShopResult> Run(ShopView view, CancellationToken token)
    {
        _cursor.Unlock();
        while (true)
        {
            var input = await NextInput(view, token);
            switch (input)
            {
                case Input.SelectItem:
                    Model = Model with { SelectedIndex = view.HoveredIndex };
                    break;
                case Input.Buy:
                    _inventory.Purchase(Model.Items[Model.SelectedIndex]);
                    Model = Model with { };
                    break;
                case Input.Close:
                    return ShopResult.Close;
            }
        }
    }
}
```

### Show/Hide

Do NOT call `view.Show()` / `view.Hide()` manually. The framework manages visibility through:
- `OpenAnimation(CancellationToken)` / `CloseAnimation(CancellationToken)` on the view
- The `RunView` lifecycle (checkout from pool -> Initialize -> Update -> Show -> wait for completion -> Hide -> release)
- Controller's `Show()` / `Hide()` methods (on the controller, not the view) orchestrate the above

### Continuous Gameplay Controllers

Per-frame simulation controllers (Player, Weapon, HUD) are a valid exception to the `Run`-as-input-only rule. These controllers:
- Use `VoidReturn` (no meaningful result)
- Run via `Enable()` (fire-and-forget) and loop until scope cancellation
- Perform per-frame simulation in `Run()` because their "input" IS the per-frame game loop

Even so, they should:
- Read tuning constants from `Model` (not hardcoded)
- Publish observable state via `AsyncReactiveProperty<T>` (not C# events)
- Move pure view-binding into `Update(TView, CT)` when practical

```csharp
// Acceptable -- per-frame gameplay controller
protected override async UniTask<VoidReturn> Run(PlayerView view, CancellationToken token)
{
    while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        await UniTask.Yield(PlayerLoopTiming.Update, token);
        // simulation logic using Model for tuning, _input for input
        // publish state for other controllers to observe
        _runtimeState.Value = new PlayerRuntimeState(...);
    }
    return default;
}
```

### Synchronous Override Convention

When `Initialize`, `Update(TView)`, or other virtual methods do no async work, do NOT use the `async` keyword. Return `UniTask.CompletedTask` or `base.Method(...)` directly. This avoids allocating an async state machine for work that completes synchronously.

```csharp
// GOOD -- no await, no async, no state machine allocation
protected override UniTask Initialize(DialogView view, CancellationToken token)
{
    view.SetMessage(Model.Message);
    return base.Initialize(view, token);
}

protected override UniTask Update(LobbyView view, CancellationToken token)
{
    view.SetPlayerCount(Model.PlayerCount);
    return UniTask.CompletedTask;
}

// BAD -- async keyword generates state machine for zero benefit
protected override async UniTask Initialize(DialogView view, CancellationToken token)
{
    view.SetMessage(Model.Message);
    await base.Initialize(view, token);
}
```

### Controller Result Types

| Pattern | Base class | When to use |
|---------|-----------|-------------|
| `Controller<TModel, TView>` | Returns `VoidReturn` | Continuous/always-on controllers (gameplay, HUD) |
| `Controller<TModel, TView, TResult>` | Returns `TResult` | Flow controllers that complete with a decision (menus, dialogs) |

Parents await flow controllers: `ResultV<TResult> result = await controller.Run(token);`
Parents fire-and-forget gameplay controllers: `controller.Enable();`

### Additional Controller Features

**ViewParent** -- Override `ViewParent` to parent a controller's view under a specific transform. Common for UI controllers that need their views under a shared canvas:

```csharp
public sealed class HudController : Controller<HudModel, HudView>
{
    [Dependency] private readonly IUICanvasService _canvas = default!;

    protected override Transform? ViewParent => _canvas.CanvasTransform;
}
```

**Control() idempotency** -- `Control(controller, token)` is safe to call multiple times. If the controller is already enabled, it returns immediately. This prevents double-enabling in reactive update loops.

## C# Conventions

- All files: `#nullable enable` at top, `#nullable disable` at bottom.
- `[Dependency]` fields: `private readonly T _field = default!;`
- `[SerializeField]` fields: `private T _field = default!;`
- Namespace: match folder path under project root (e.g., `DeepForestLabs.Slumber.States`).
